05183nam a22009015i 9783110691351DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106913517 a10.1515/97831106913512doi  a(DE-B1597)544609  a(OCoLC)1163878482  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a1001 aChikurel, Idit, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSalomon Maimon’s Theory of Invention :bScientific Genius, Analysis and Euclidean Geometry /cIdit Chikurel. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (X, 168 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1: The Genius and the Methodical Inventor -- tChapter 2: An Art of Finding Arguments -- tChapter 3: Invention, Analysis and Synthesis -- tChapter 4: Methods of Invention -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Terms -- tIndex of Person0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow can we invent new certain knowledge in a methodical manner? This question stands at the heart of Salomon Maimon's theory of invention. Chikurel argues that Maimon's contribution to the ars inveniendi tradition lies in the methods of invention which he prescribes for mathematics. Influenced by Proclus' commentary on Elements, these methods are applied on examples taken from Euclid's Elements and Data. Centering around methodical invention and scientific genius, Maimon's philosophy is unique in an era glorifying the artistic genius, known as Geniezeit. Invention, primarily defined as constructing syllogisms, has implications on the notion of being given in intuition as well as in symbolic cognition. Chikurel introduces Maimon's notion of analysis in the broader sense, grounded not only on the principle of contradiction but on intuition as well. In philosophy, ampliative analysis is based on Maimon's logical term of analysis of the object, a term that has yet to be discussed in Maimonian scholarship. Following its introduction, a new version of the question quid juris? arises. In mathematics, Chikurel demonstrates how this conception of analysis originates from practices of Greek geometrical analysis.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 4aAnalyse. 4aErfindung. 4aEuklidische Geometrie. 4aSalomon Maimon. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aEuclidean Geometry.  aSalomon Maimon.  aanalysis.  ainvention.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020 Englishz978311070482208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020z9783110704648oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831106914120 cprintz978311069133740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311069135140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110691351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110691351/original  a978-3-11-065906-1  De Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCb2020  a978-3-11-069627-1  DG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1b2020  a978-3-11-069628-8  DG Ebook Package English 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070482-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Ph